00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:16.180
And one thing I'd like to add to this Frozen Dict that I think is super interesting.

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:19.820
We've had other Frozen types like Set, I think, and List.

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:29.880
But in this Python T, the free-threaded Python world, one of the things that can really unlock concurrency

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:34.820
is not having to worry about locking on different objects.

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:37.980
If you work with Frozen Dicts, it's read-only.

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:41.940
And you can just have all the threads ram on it all at once, right?

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:44.600
You don't have to worry about locks once it's created.

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:50.120
So, people just consider adopting immutable data types in general when possible.

00:13:50.220 --> 00:13:58.920
Like, if you're creating a Dict, but you're not going to change it, Frozen Dict seems like something cool to put in place that, like, adds a little more security.

00:13:59.180 --> 00:14:03.840
So, like, if you don't expect it to change, like, you can set it up now so it cannot change.

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:05.280
Yeah.

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:11.400
And even things that generally we think of changing, you can use data flows, like, algorithmic stuff to do.

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:12.960
So, that's functional.

00:14:13.180 --> 00:14:22.140
Like you said, it's a functional model for some part of your system that can be easily asynced because it's all immutable types.

00:14:22.580 --> 00:14:23.000
So, yeah.

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:23.740
Yeah.

