Well, why, yes, we do.

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:08.340
It has, like, all these really nice, deep understanding of, like, the hierarchy of stuff.

00:20:08.420 --> 00:20:09.900
It's not just, like, a regular search, right?

00:20:09.980 --> 00:20:11.420
Like, it's something I put together.

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:16.580
But it's still, this is a ridiculous amount, 700 megs for something that just, like, reads from the database and writes to the database.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:18.500
And otherwise, it's doing nothing.

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:21.200
So, I'm like, well, how can I do this better?

00:20:21.460 --> 00:20:25.820
The first thing I did, there's five things I'm going to talk about pretty quick.

00:20:25.820 --> 00:20:40.060
Number one is I was running two to three worker processes to scale out web requests because everything was still based on Pyramid, in which case it's synchronous, it's WSGI.

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:55.800
And so, I really wanted to have, like, if I'm going to have fewer processes, then I really want to have better concurrency in the one worker process.

00:20:55.820 --> 00:20:56.640
That's there, right?

00:20:56.680 --> 00:21:00.640
I don't want, like, one slow request to be just like, well, that's it.

00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:02.820
The site's not responding, right?

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:03.380
Because of the kill.

00:21:06.580 --> 00:21:07.300
Sorry about that.

00:21:07.480 --> 00:21:16.940
So, I decided the first thing to do is to rewrite everything in court.

00:21:17.240 --> 00:21:21.900
And it could be other languages, anything that's async.

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:30.060
Well, in court is the true async version of Flask, right?

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:30.960
Yeah.

00:21:30.960 --> 00:21:32.440
So, that's what I did.

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:40.260
And that let me turn it, turn the other worker process off, which right there just cuts your memory straight in half, right?

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:42.940
Because they both use the same amount of memory, and there's two of them.

00:21:43.640 --> 00:21:45.180
And, you know, people think, like, oh, yeah, whatever.

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:47.560
Like, Michael, your site's just a blog.

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:48.720
Like, dude, what are you talking about?

00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:51.220
Like, you seem to think, like, there's a lot going on here.

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:54.320
But I work on a real app, so it doesn't apply to me.

00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:59.320
I ran my little tallyman thing against Talk Python training.

00:21:59.420 --> 00:22:01.680
Not any of the podcasts, just the courses.

00:22:02.680 --> 00:22:06.240
178,000 lines of Python, 300,000 lines total.

00:22:06.460 --> 00:22:09.600
Like, that's enough to, like, spend some time figuring out what's going on, right?

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:12.640
That's complicated enough for most apps, I imagine.

00:22:13.340 --> 00:22:14.740
At least to be somewhat representative.

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:18.240
Yeah, but you're, like, running courses and podcasts and stuff.

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:19.940
This is more complicated than just a blog.

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:21.200
Yeah, that's true.

00:22:21.420 --> 00:22:21.820
That's true.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:23.320
Yeah, but tell Reddit that.

00:22:23.320 --> 00:22:32.260
So then the next thing, the number two, was I'm going to rewrite this in that the raw plus DC design pattern that I talked about.

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:36.880
Just using straight queries, not ORMs or ODMs.

00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:39.240
Although I have something interesting to say my extra about that.

00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:42.340
But still, just straight queries and then mapping data classes.

00:22:42.520 --> 00:22:44.300
Or it could be pedantic or adders, right?

00:22:44.320 --> 00:22:44.940
It doesn't really matter.

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:47.180
Pick a model, a simple data model.

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:50.180
And that actually made a pretty big difference.

00:22:50.180 --> 00:23:00.000
That dropped 200 megs per worker, just switching away from an ORM to just raw queries and data classes.

00:23:01.340 --> 00:23:02.060
Makes sense.

00:23:02.600 --> 00:23:06.840
And it almost doubled the request per second, which is wild.

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:08.980
Okay, so then number three.

00:23:11.100 --> 00:23:17.360
Well, once I had done the court thing, I was able to just tell Granny, like, I want one worker, not two.

00:23:17.860 --> 00:23:18.320
Or three.

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.380
For a while it was three or four, and I've been, like, dialing it back.

00:23:21.460 --> 00:23:22.120
It's just got faster.

00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:24.800
So that saved 500 megs there.

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:29.040
So now we're down to, yeah, we're down to 530 megs for this process.

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:36.820
And then for the search thing, what was happening is it would load up a bunch of imports.

00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:39.560
810, getting exciting here.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:40.780
It would load up a bunch of imports.

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:54.680
And then it would run a bunch of code that would, like, get all, I don't know exactly where the memory was going, but a lot of stuff that it would work with by doing, interact with the database and so on, would get cached or just left in memory.

00:23:54.680 --> 00:24:00.140
So it was using 708 megs of memory.

00:24:00.920 --> 00:24:13.380
So I said, well, what if, like, really the main core loop of the app is just start, look at a timer, after a certain amount of time, run a really complicated set of queries,

00:24:13.380 --> 00:24:20.840
queries, and then write a bunch of structured data indexed back into a certain structure so I can query it ultra fast, right?

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:32.520
That main part doesn't need, it was importing, like, all the library, like, all of Talk Python training, which would pull in everything that Talk Python training's main dunder.

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:37.320
And it would pull in, which would pull in all the libraries that every, you know, it would cascade into this mega import.

00:24:37.320 --> 00:24:50.120
So I said, well, what if you just had the loop and then in a separate file you ran, you would start a process that ran that separate file that did the indexing and then stopped

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:52.800
and, like, just finished, like, because it didn't need a response.

00:24:52.880 --> 00:24:54.280
It was like, okay, I'm done indexing.

00:24:54.720 --> 00:25:02.100
And that temporary subprocess would be the thing that did all the imports, and when it shuts down, those imports go away.

00:25:02.180 --> 00:25:05.220
So that took it from 708 megs to 22.

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:07.280
That's great.

00:25:07.560 --> 00:25:08.740
That's insane, right?

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:16.240
Yeah, so that subprocess is still getting, like, 700 megs or whatever, but it goes away.

00:25:16.700 --> 00:25:20.120
But for, like, 30 seconds to a minute, not constantly, right?

00:25:20.380 --> 00:25:25.960
And these spikes are, I mean, they're fine, but it's like, you know, not everything is spiking in memory at the same time, just like they don't in CPU.

00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:30.980
It's just, like, it's not a fixed cost, which is pretty interesting.

00:25:30.980 --> 00:25:43.140
You know, the work was just like, I'm just going to do the index, move the indexing function to a new file, move the imports that it needs to a new file, and just do a subprocess to call it instead of calling it directly.

00:25:43.500 --> 00:25:43.840
Done.

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:44.140
Yeah.

00:25:44.140 --> 00:25:48.900
And it made, I don't know what that division is, but like 20 times, 30 times better.

00:25:49.400 --> 00:25:50.760
You know, it's incredible.

00:25:50.760 --> 00:26:00.020
And the last thing, this one I think is going to surprise people, and this is the one that really hits the point home for lazy imports.

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:11.640
If you type the words import Boto3, because you're doing something with S3 or something similar, your working memory goes up by 25 megs per process, per worker process.

00:26:12.120 --> 00:26:17.180
If you type the words import matplotlib, your working memory goes up by 17 megs.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:20.200
If you type import pandas, your memory goes up by 44 megs.

00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:23.860
Those three imports right there are almost 100 megs of memory usage.

00:26:25.420 --> 00:26:26.540
Yeah, it's a lot.

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:29.160
So are they needed?

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:30.940
If you're doing core data science, they are.

00:26:32.200 --> 00:26:38.240
But for me, there's like an admin section where I can go and view some reports.

00:26:38.740 --> 00:26:41.120
If I view the reports, I use these libraries.

00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:47.340
But if I don't view the reports, which I really don't look at them hardly ever, just like maybe once a month, like, hey, I wonder what that looks like.

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:48.340
Let me go hit it.

00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:52.260
It pulls all that stuff in, and then it generates the report.

00:26:54.080 --> 00:26:58.200
But the worker process recycles a couple times a day.

00:26:58.200 --> 00:26:58.640
Yeah.

00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:08.120
And so even if I view the report, five hours later, that stuff's unloaded again, and I get a new version, and it's not another month until I load up that 100 megs.

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:22.280
So I went from like 500 megs to 450 just by saying, well, instead of importing the top of the file, let's import in the function that generates the actual picture, you know, the report that I need from this.

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:25.680
And boom, 100 megs less memory usage.

00:27:26.120 --> 00:27:30.040
And if that had the word lazy in front of it, I wouldn't have to rewrite my code.

00:27:30.040 --> 00:27:33.180
And it would have effectively the same behavior.

00:27:33.420 --> 00:27:35.120
It wouldn't import until I actually run the function.

00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:38.240
But I could do PEP 8 magic and put it at the top.

00:27:38.340 --> 00:27:39.000
What do you think of that?

00:27:39.760 --> 00:27:40.540
That's pretty cool.

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:46.280
So now I'm thinking that, like, lazy imports, it imports when it's needed, but it doesn't ever unimport.

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:57.300
And I'm wondering if, like, a future Python will add, like, you know, something to the lazy import that, like, caches stuff out of memory later.

00:27:57.300 --> 00:27:57.660
Right, right, right.

00:27:57.660 --> 00:27:58.400
It's not being used.

00:27:58.780 --> 00:28:06.780
The runtime could see nobody is caring about it being imported anymore, and no one has set a value on it, so maybe it could just go away 100%.

00:28:06.780 --> 00:28:13.460
But that means, I mean, people, I think, often think of lazy import as something that's a speed up.

00:28:13.460 --> 00:28:18.660
Like, oh, it's faster because you don't have to do all the imports until you use them.

00:28:19.020 --> 00:28:19.980
I'm sure that's true.

00:28:20.080 --> 00:28:21.080
I don't have numbers around it.

00:28:21.400 --> 00:28:27.640
But what's really interesting is there are some imports that are mega in amount, how much they actually increase your working memory.

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:33.380
If they're lazy and you don't use them very often, they will not run very often.

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:35.720
And I think it will actually make a pretty big difference.

00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:40.900
So, you know, like, you just write code, like, just do import inside the function instead of at the top.

00:28:40.900 --> 00:28:42.740
Like, your lenders will go, you shouldn't do this.

00:28:42.740 --> 00:28:43.820
Like, you leave me alone.

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:44.500
I'm doing this.

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:46.120
This is really good for me.

00:28:46.960 --> 00:28:53.160
So, and the final thing, I just moved a bunch of caches to disk caches instead of memory caches, which is good.

00:28:54.040 --> 00:29:01.100
And so I put a little picture in there, but it saved a ton of memory across.

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:06.880
3.2 gigs less memory used on the server by applying that to Python Bytes, Talk Python, and Talk Python Training.

